# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: powerlink
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:powerlink/ethernet-powerlink] This protocol has nothing to do with power distribution via Ethernet cabling or power over Ethernet (PoE), power line communication, or Bang & Olufsen's PowerLink cable.
[src:powerlink/ethernet-powerlink] Ethernet Powerlink expands Ethernet with a mixed polling and timeslicing mechanism.
[src:powerlink/ethernet-powerlink] Modern implementations reach cycle-times of under 200 μs and a time-precision (jitter) of less than 1 μs.
[src:powerlink/ethernet-powerlink] Powerlink was standardized by the Ethernet Powerlink Standardization Group (EPSG) and founded in June 2003 as an independent association.
[src:powerlink/ethernet-powerlink] Working groups focus on tasks like safety, technology, marketing, certification and end users.
[src:powerlink/ethernet-powerlink] The EPSG cooperates with the standardization bodies and associations, like the CAN in Automation (CiA) Group and the IEC.
[src:powerlink/ethernet-powerlink] The original physical layer specified was 100BASE-TX Fast Ethernet.
[src:powerlink/ethernet-powerlink] Since the end of 2006, Ethernet Powerlink with Gigabit Ethernet supported a transmission rate ten times higher (1,000 Mbit/s).
[src:powerlink/ethernet-powerlink] Repeating hubs instead of switches within the real-time domain is recommended to minimise delay and jitter.
[src:powerlink/ethernet-powerlink] Ethernet Powerlink uses IAONA's Industrial Ethernet Planning and Installation Guide for clean cabling of industrial networks and both industrial Ethernet connectors 8P8C (commonly known as RJ45) and M12 are accepted.
[src:powerlink/ethernet-powerlink] The standard Ethernet data link layer is extended by an additional bus scheduling mechanism, which guarantees that only one node at a time is accessing the network.
[src:powerlink/ethernet-powerlink] The schedule is divided into an isochronous phase and an asynchronous phase.
[src:powerlink/ethernet-powerlink] During the isochronous phase, time-critical data is transferred, while the asynchronous phase provides bandwidth for the transmission of non time-critical data.
[src:powerlink/ethernet-powerlink] The Managing Node (MN) grants access to the physical medium via dedicated poll request messages.
[src:powerlink/ethernet-powerlink] As a result, only one single node (CN) has access to the network at a time, which avoids collisions, present on older Ethernet hubs before switches.
[src:powerlink/ethernet-powerlink] The CSMA/CD mechanism of non-switched Ethernet, which caused non-deterministic Ethernet behaviour, is avoided by the Ethernet Powerlink scheduling mechanism.
[src:powerlink/ethernet-powerlink] After system start-up is finished, the real-time domain is operating under real-time conditions.
[src:powerlink/ethernet-powerlink] The scheduling of the basic cycle is controlled by the Managing Node (MN).
[src:powerlink/ethernet-powerlink] The overall cycle time depends on the amount of isochronous data, asynchronous data and the number of nodes to be polled during each cycle.
[src:powerlink/ethernet-powerlink] The time frame which includes Preq-n and Pres-n is called time slot for the addressed node.
[src:powerlink/ethernet-powerlink] The quality of the Real-Time behavior depends on the precision of the overall basic cycle time.
[src:powerlink/ethernet-powerlink] The length of individual phases can vary as long as the total of all phases remain within the basic cycle time boundaries.
[src:powerlink/ethernet-powerlink] Adherence to the basic cycle time is monitored by the Managing Node.
[src:powerlink/ethernet-powerlink] The duration of the isochronous and the asynchronous phase can be configured.
[src:powerlink/ethernet-powerlink] In addition to transferring isochronous data during each basic cycle, some nodes are also able to share transfer slots for better bandwidth utilization.
[src:powerlink/ethernet-powerlink] For that reason, the isochronous phase can distinguish between transfer slots dedicated to particular nodes, which have to send their data in every basic cycle, and slots shared by nodes to transfer their data one after the other in different cycles.
[src:powerlink/ethernet-powerlink] Therefore, less important yet still time-critical data can be transferred in longer cycles than the basic cycle.
[src:powerlink/ethernet-powerlink] Assigning the slots during each cycle is at the discretion of the Managing Node.
[src:powerlink/ethernet-powerlink] Mode used mainly for robotics applications and large superstructures.
[src:powerlink/ethernet-powerlink] Key is a lower number of frames and better data distribution.
[src:powerlink/ethernet-powerlink] Today, machines, plants and safety systems are stuck in a rigid scheme made up of hardware-based safety functions.
[src:powerlink/ethernet-powerlink] The consequences of this are cost-intensive cabling and limited diagnostic options.
[src:powerlink/ethernet-powerlink] The solution is the integration of safety relevant application data into the standard serial control protocol.
[src:powerlink/ethernet-powerlink] OpenSAFETY allows both publish/subscriber and client/server communication.
[src:powerlink/ethernet-powerlink] Safety relevant data is transmitted via an embedded data frame inside of standard communication messages.
[src:powerlink/ethernet-powerlink] Measures to avoid any undetected failures due to systematic or stochastic errors are an integral part of a functional safety protocol.
[src:powerlink/ethernet-powerlink] OpenSAFETY is in conformance with IEC 61508.
[src:powerlink/ethernet-powerlink] The protocol fulfills the requirements of SIL 3.
[src:powerlink/ethernet-powerlink] Error detection techniques have no impact on existing transport layers.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] A **fieldbus** is a member of a family of industrial digital communication networks used for real-time distributed control.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] Fieldbus profiles are standardized by the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) as IEC 61784/61158.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] A complex automated industrial system is typically structured in hierarchical levels as a distributed control system (DCS).
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] In this hierarchy the upper levels for production managements are linked to the direct control level of programmable logic controllers (PLC) via a non-time-critical communications system (e.g.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] The fieldbus links the PLCs of the direct control level to the components in the plant at the field level, such as sensors, actuators, electric motors, console lights, switches, valves and contactors.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] It also replaces the direct connections via current loops or digital I/O signals.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] The requirements for a fieldbus are therefore time-critical and cost-sensitive.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] Since the new millennium, a number of fieldbuses based on Real-time Ethernet have been established.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] These have the potential to replace traditional fieldbuses in the long term.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] A fieldbus is an industrial network system for real-time distributed control.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] It is a way to connect instruments in a manufacturing plant.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] A fieldbus works on a network structure which typically allows daisy-chain, star, ring, branch, and tree network topologies.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] Previously, computers were connected using RS-232 (serial connections) by which only two devices could communicate.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] This reduces both the length of and total number of cables required.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] Furthermore, since devices that communicate through a fieldbus require a microprocessor, multiple points are typically provided by the same device.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] Some fieldbus devices now support control schemes such as PID control on the device-side instead of forcing the controller to do the processing.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] The most important motivation to use a fieldbus in a distributed control system is to reduce the cost for installation and maintenance of the installation without losing the high availability and reliability of the automation system.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] The goal is to use a two wire cable and simple configuration for field devices from different manufacturers.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] Depending on the application, the number of sensors and actuators vary from hundreds in one machine up to several thousands distributed over a large plant.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] The history of the fieldbus demonstrates how these goals have been approached over time.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] Arguably the precursor field bus technology is HP-IB as described in IEEE 488 in 1975.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] "It became known as the General Purpose Interface Bus (GPIB), and became a de facto standard for automated and industrial instrument control".
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] The GPIB has its main application in automated measurements with instruments from different manufacturers.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] It is a parallel bus with a cable and connector with 24 wires, limited to a maximal cable length of 20 metres.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] The oldest commonly used field bus technology is Bitbus.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] Bitbus was created by Intel Corporation to enhance use of Multibus systems in industrial systems by separating slow i/o functions from faster memory access.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] In 1983, Intel created the 8044 Bitbus microcontroller by adding field bus firmware to its existing 8051 microcontroller.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] Bitbus uses EIA-485 at the physical layer, with two twisted pairs - one for data and the other for clocking and signals.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] Use of SDLC at the data link layer permits 250 nodes on one segment with a total distance of 13.2 km.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] Bitbus has one master node and multiple slaves, with slaves only responding to requests from the master.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] Bitbus does not define routing at the network layer.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] The 8044 permits only a relatively small data packet (13 bytes), but embeds an efficient set of RAC (remote access and control) tasks and the ability to develop custom RAC tasks.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] In 1990, the IEEE adopted Bitbus as the Microcontroller System Serial Control Bus (IEEE-1118).
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] Today BITBUS is maintained by the BEUG - BITBUS European Users Group.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] Office networks are not really suited for automation applications, as they lack the upper-bounded transmission delay.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] ARCNET, which was conceived as early as 1975 for office connectivity uses a token mechanism and therefore found later uses in industry.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] The Manufacturing Automation Protocol (MAP) was an implementation of OSI-compliant protocols in automation technology initiated by General Motors in 1984.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] MAP became a LAN standardization proposal supported by many manufacturers and was mainly used in factory automation.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] MAP used the 10 Mbit/s IEEE 802.4 token bus as a transmission medium.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] Due to its scope and complexity, MAP failed to make a big breakthrough.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] To reduce the complexity and reach faster processing with reduced resources the Enhanced Performance Architecture (EPA) MAP was developed in 1988.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] This MiniMap contains only levels 1, 2, and 7 of the Open Systems Interconnection (OSI) basic reference model.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] This shortcut was taken over by later fieldbus definitions.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] The most important achievement of MAP is Manufacturing Message Specification (MMS), the application layer of MAP.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] The Manufacturing Message Specification (MMS) is an international standard ISO 9506 dealing with an application protocol and services for transferring real time process data and supervisory control information between networked devices or computer applications published as a first version in 1986.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] It has been a model for many further developments in other industrial communication standardizations such as FMS for Profibus or SDO for CANopen.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] It is still in use as a possible application layer e.g. for power utility automation in the IEC 61850 standards.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] In the field of manufacturing automation the requirements for a fieldbus are to support short reaction times with only a few bits or bytes to be transmitted over not more than some hundreds of meters.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] In 1979 Modicon (now Schneider Electric) defined a serial bus to connect their programmable logic controllers (PLCs) called Modbus.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] In its first version Modbus used a two wire cable with EIA 485 UART signals.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] The protocol itself is very simple with a master/slave protocol and the number of data types are limited to those understood by PLCs at the time.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] Nevertheless, Modbus is (with its Modbus-TCP version) still one of the most used industrial networks, mainly in the building automation field.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] A research project with the financial support of the German government defined in 1987 the fieldbus PROFIBUS based on the *Fieldbus Message Specification* (FMS).
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] In practical applications, it proved too complicated to handle in the field.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] In 1994 Siemens proposed a modified application layer with the name *Decentralized Periphery* (DP) which reached a good acceptance in the manufacturing industry.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] As of 2016, the Profibus is one of the most installed fieldbuses in the world and reached 60 million installed nodes in 2018.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] In 1987 Phoenix Contact developed a serial bus to connect spatially distributed inputs and outputs to a centralized controller.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] The controller sends one frame over a physical ring, which contains all input and output data.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] The cable has 5 wires: besides the ground signal, two wires for the outgoing frame and two wires for the returning frame.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] With this cable is it possible to have the whole installation in a tree topology.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] The INTERBUS was very successful in the manufacturing industry with more than 22,9 million devices installed in the field.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] The Interbus joined the Profinet technology for Ethernet-based fieldbus Profinet and the INTERBUS is now maintained by the Profibus Nutzerorganisation e.V.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] During the 1980s, to solve communication problems between different control systems in cars, the German company Robert Bosch GmbH first developed the Controller Area Network (CAN).
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] The concept of CAN was that every device can be connected by a single set of wires, and every device that is connected can freely exchange data with any other device.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] CAN soon migrated into the factory automation marketplace (with many others).
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] In process automation traditionally most of the field transmitters are connected over a current loop with 4-20 mA to the controlling device.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] This allows not only to transmit the measured value with the level of the current, but also provide the required electrical power to the field device with just one two-wire cable of a length of more than a thousand meters.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] These systems are also installed in hazardous areas.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] According to NAMUR a fieldbus in these applications has to fulfill these requirements.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] A special standard for instrumentation, IEC/EN 60079-27, describes requirements for the Fieldbus Intrinsically Safe Concept (FISCO) for installations in zone 0, 1 or 2.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] The FIP standard is based on a French initiative in 1982 to create a requirements analysis for a future field bus standard.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] The study led to the European Eureka initiative for a field bus standard in June 1986 that included 13 partners.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] The development group (réseaux locaux industriels) created the first proposal to be standardized in France.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] The name of the FIP field bus was originally given as an abbreviation of the French "Flux d'Information vers le Processus" while later referring to FIP with the English name "Factory Instrumentation Protocol".
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] FIP has lost ground to Profibus which came to prevail the market in Europe in the following decade - the WorldFIP homepage has seen no press release since 2002.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] The closest cousin of the FIP family can be found today in the Wire Train Bus for train coaches.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] However a specific subset of WorldFIP - known the FIPIO protocol - can be found widely in machine components.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] Foundation Fieldbus was developed over a period of many years by the International Society of Automation (ISA) as SP50.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] Foundation Fieldbus today enjoys a growing installed base in many heavy process applications such as refining, petrochemicals, power generation, and even food and beverage, pharmaceuticals, and nuclear applications.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] Effective January 1, 2015, the Fieldbus Foundation has become part of the new FieldComm Group.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] Profibus PA (process automation) is used for communication between measuring and process instruments, actuators and process control system or PLC/DCS in process engineering.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] Profibus PA is a Profibus version with physical layer suitable for process automation, in which several segments (PA segments) with field instruments can be connected to Profibus DP via so-called couplers.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] The two-wire bus cable of these segments takes over not only the communication, but also the power supply of the participants (MBP transmission technology).
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] Another special feature of Profibus PA is the widely used device profile "PA Devices" (PA Profile), in which the most important functions of the field devices are standardized across manufacturers.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] The BatiBUS defined in 1989 and used mainly in France, the Instabus extended to the European Installation Bus (EIB) and the European Home Systems Protocol (EHS) merged in 1999 to the Konnex) (KNX) standard EN 50090, (ISO/IEC 14543-3).
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] In 2020 495 Member companies offer 8'000 products with KNX interfaces in 190 countries worldwide.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] Going back to the 1980s, unlike other networks, LonWorks is the result of the work of computer scientists from Echelon Corporation.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] In 1999 the communications protocol (then known as LonTalk) was submitted to ANSI and accepted as a standard for control networking (ANSI/CEA-709.1-B), in 2005 as EN 14908 (European building automation standard).
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] The protocol is also one of several data link/physical layers of the BACnet ASHRAE/ANSI standard for building automation.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] The BACnet standard was initially developed and is now maintained by the American Society of Heating, Refrigerating and Air-Conditioning Engineers (ASHRAE) starting in 1987.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] BACnet is an American National Standard (ANSI) 135 since 1995, a European standard, a national standard in many countries, and global ISO Standard 16484 since 2003.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] BACnet has in 2017 a market share of 60% in building automation market.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] Although fieldbus technology has been around since 1988, with the completion of the ISA S50.02 standard, the development of the international standard took many years.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] In 1999, the IEC SC65C/WG6 standards committee met to resolve difference in the draft IEC fieldbus standard.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] The result of this meeting was the initial form of the IEC 61158 standard with eight different protocol sets called "Types".
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] This form of standard was first developed for the European Common Market, concentrates less on commonality, and achieves its primary purpose—elimination of restraint of trade between nations.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] Issues of commonality are now left to the international consortia that support each of the fieldbus standard types.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] Almost as soon as it was approved, the IEC standards development work ceased and the committee was dissolved.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] A new IEC committee SC65C/MT-9 was formed to resolve the conflicts in form and substance within the more than 4000 pages of IEC 61158.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] The work on the above protocol types is substantially complete.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] New protocols, such as for safety fieldbuses or real-time Ethernet fieldbuses are being accepted into the definition of the international fieldbus standard during a typical 5-year maintenance cycle.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] In the 2008 version of the standard, the fieldbus types are reorganized into Communication Profile Families (CPFs).
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] There were many competing technologies for fieldbuses and the original hope for one single unified communications mechanism has not been realized.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] This should not be unexpected since fieldbus technology needs to be implemented differently in different applications; automotive fieldbuses are functionally different from process plant control fieldbuses.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] In June 1999 the IEC's Committee of Action (CA) decided to take a new structure for the fieldbus standards beginning with a first edition valid at the January 1, 2000, in time for the new millennium: There is a large IEC 61158 standard, where all fieldbuses find their place.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] The experts have decided that the structure of IEC 61158 is maintained according to different layers, divided into services and protocols.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] The individual fieldbuses are incorporated into this structure as different types.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] Each part still contains several thousand pages.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] Therefore, these parts have been further subdivided into subparts.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] The individual protocols have simply been numbered with a type.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] Each protocol type thus has its own subpart if required.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] In order to find the corresponding subpart of the individual parts of the IEC 61158 standard, one must know the corresponding protocol type for a specific family.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] In the 2019 edition of IEC 61158 up to 26 different types of protocols are specified.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] In IEC 61158 standardization, the use of brand names is avoided and replaced by dry technical terms and abbreviations.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] For example, Ethernet is replaced by the technically correct CSMA/CD or a reference to the corresponding ISO standard 8802.3.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] This is also the case with fieldbus names, they all are replaced by type numbers.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] The reader will therefore never find a designation such as PROFIBUS or DeviceNet in the entire IEC 61158 fieldbus standard.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] In the section Compliance to IEC 61784 a complete reference table is provided.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] It is clear that this collection of fieldbus standards in IEC 61158 is not suitable for implementation.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] It must be supplemented with instructions for use.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] These instructions show how and which parts of IEC 61158 can be assembled to a functioning system.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] This assembly instruction has been compiled subsequently as IEC 61784 fieldbus profiles.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] The IEC 61784 Part 1 standard with the name *Profile sets for continuous and discrete manufacturing relative to fieldbus use in industrial control systems* lists all fieldbuses which are proposed by the national standardization bodies.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] Swiftnet, which is widely used in aircraft construction (Boeing), was included in the first edition of the standard.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] This later proves to be a mistake and in the 2007 edition 2 this protocol was removed from the standard.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] At the same time, the CPF 8 CC-Link, the CPF 9 HART protocol and CPF 16 SERCOS are added.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] In the edition 4 in 2014 the last fieldbus CPF 19 MECHATROLINK was included into the standard.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] The edition 5 in 2019 was just a maintenance revision without any new profile added.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] See List of automation protocols for fieldbuses that are not included in this standard.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] Already in edition 2 of the fieldbus profile first profiles based on Ethernet as physical layer are included.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] All this new developed Real-time Ethernet (RTE) protocols are compiled in IEC 61784 Part 2 as *Additional profiles for ISO/IEC 8802 3 based communication networks in real-time applications*.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] The SERCOS solution is interesting in this context.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] This network from the field of axis control had its own standard IEC 61491.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] With the introduction of the Ethernet-based solution SERCOS III, this standard has been taken apart and the communication part is integrated in IEC 61158/61784.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] The application part has been integrated together with other drive solutions into a special drive standard IEC 61800-7.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] In 2010, a second edition was published to include CPF 17 RAPIEnet and CPF 18 SafetyNET p.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] In the third edition (2014), the Industrial Ethernet (IE) version of CC-Link was added.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] The two profile families CPF 20 ADS-net and CPF 19 FL-net were added to the fourth edition in 2019.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] For details about these RTEs see the article on Industrial Ethernet.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] For functional safety, different consortia have developed different protocols for safety applications up to Safety Integrity Level 3 (SIL) according to IEC 61508 or Performance Level "e" (PL) according to ISO 13849.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] What most solutions have in common is that they are based on a *Black Channel* and can therefore be transmitted via different fieldbuses and networks.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] Depending on the actual profile the safety protocol does provide measures like counters, CRCs, echo, timeout, unique sender and receiver IDs or cross check.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] SERCOS does use the *CIP safety* protocol as well.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] In the third edition in 2016 the last safety profile CPF 17 SafetyNET p was added.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] A new edition 4 is expected to be published in 2021.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] The standard has now 9 different safety profiles.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] They are all included and referenced in the global compliance table in the next section.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] The protocol families of each brand name are called Communication Profile Family and are abbreviated as CPF with a number.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] Each protocol family can now define fieldbuses, real-time Ethernet solutions, installation rules and protocols for functional safety.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] These possible profile families are laid down in IEC 61784 and compiled in the following table.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] As an example, we will search for the standards for PROFIBUS-DP.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] This belongs to the CPF 3 family and has the profile CP 3/1.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] In Table 5 we find that its protocol scope is defined in IEC 61784 Part 1.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] The physical interface is defined in the common 61158-2 under type 3.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] The installation regulations can be found in IEC 61784-5-3 in Appendix A.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] It can be combined with the FSCP3/1 as PROFIsafe, which is defined in the IEC 61784-3-3 standard.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] To avoid the manufacturer having to list all these standards explicitly, the reference to the profile is specified in the standard.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] Discrete fieldbus networks are often referred to as "device networks".
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] Already in the year 2000 the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) decided that a set of *controller-device interfaces* (CDIs) will be specified by the Technical Committee TC 121 *Low-voltage switchgear and controlgear* to cover the device networks.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] The amount of cabling required is much lower in fieldbus than in 4–20 mA installations.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] This is because many devices share the same set of cables in a multi-dropped fashion rather than requiring a dedicated set of cables per device as in the case of 4–20 mA devices.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] Moreover, several parameters can be communicated per device in a fieldbus network whereas only one parameter can be transmitted on a 4–20 mA connection.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] A fieldbus also provides a good foundation for the creation of a predictive and proactive maintenance strategy.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] The diagnostics available from fieldbus devices can be used to address issues with devices before they become critical problems.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] Despite each technology sharing the generic name of fieldbus the various fieldbuses are not readily interchangeable.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] The differences between them are so profound that they cannot be easily connected to each other.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] To understand the differences among fieldbus standards, it is necessary to understand how fieldbus networks are designed.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] With reference to the OSI model, fieldbus standards are determined by the physical media of the cabling, and layers one, two and seven of the reference model.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] For each technology the physical medium and the physical layer standards fully describe, in detail, the implementation of bit timing, synchronization, encoding/decoding, band rate, bus length and the physical connection of the transceiver to the communication wires.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] The data link layer standard is responsible for fully specifying how messages are assembled ready for transmission by the physical layer, error handling, message-filtering and bus arbitration and how these standards are to be implemented in hardware.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] The application layer standard, in general defines how the data communication layers are interfaced to the application that wishes to communicate.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] It describes message specifications, network management implementations and response to the request from the application of services.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] Layers three to six are not described in fieldbus standards.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] Different fieldbuses offer different sets of features and performance.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] It is difficult to make a general comparison of fieldbus performance because of fundamental differences in data transfer methodology.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] In the comparison table below it is simply noted if the fieldbus in question typically supports data update cycles of 1 millisecond or faster.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] As of 2008, in process control systems, the market is dominated by Foundation Fieldbus and Profibus PA.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] Both technologies use the same physical layer (2-wire Manchester-encoded current modulation at 31.25 kHz) but are not interchangeable.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] As a general guide, applications which are controlled and monitored by programmable logic controllers (PLCs) tend towards PROFIBUS, and applications which are controlled and monitored by a digital/distributed control system (DCS) tend towards Foundation Fieldbus.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] PROFIBUS technology is made available through Profibus International with headquarters in Karlsruhe, Germany.
[src:powerlink/fieldbus] Foundation Fieldbus technology is owned and distributed by the Fieldbus Foundation of Austin, Texas.
[src:powerlink/industrial-ethernet] Industrial Ethernet can also refer to the use of standard Ethernet protocols with rugged connectors and extended temperature switches in an industrial environment, for automation or process control.
[src:powerlink/industrial-ethernet] Components used in plant process areas must be designed to work in harsh environments of temperature extremes, humidity, and vibration that exceed the ranges for information technology equipment intended for installation in controlled environments.
[src:powerlink/industrial-ethernet] The use of fiber-optic Ethernet variants reduces the problems of electrical noise and provides electrical isolation.
[src:powerlink/industrial-ethernet] Some industrial networks emphasized deterministic delivery of transmitted data, whereas Ethernet used collision detection which made transport time for individual data packets difficult to estimate with increasing network traffic.
[src:powerlink/industrial-ethernet] Typically, industrial uses of Ethernet employ full-duplex standards and other methods so that collisions do not unacceptably influence transmission times.
[src:powerlink/industrial-ethernet] Industrial use requires consideration of the environment in which the equipment must operate.
[src:powerlink/industrial-ethernet] Factory equipment must tolerate a wider range of temperature, vibration, physical contamination and electrical noise than equipment installed in dedicated information-technology wiring closets.
[src:powerlink/industrial-ethernet] Since critical process control may rely on an Ethernet link, the economic cost of interruptions may be high and high availability is therefore an essential criterion.
[src:powerlink/industrial-ethernet] Industrial Ethernet networks must interoperate with both current and legacy systems, and must provide predictable performance and maintainability.
[src:powerlink/industrial-ethernet] In addition to physical compatibility and low-level transport protocols, a practical industrial Ethernet system must also provide interoperability of higher levels of the OSI model.
[src:powerlink/industrial-ethernet] An industrial network must provide security both from intrusions from outside the plant, and inadvertent or unauthorized use within the plant.
[src:powerlink/industrial-ethernet] When an industrial network must connect to an office network or external networks, a firewall system can be inserted to control exchange of data between the networks.
[src:powerlink/industrial-ethernet] This network separation preserves the performance and reliability of the industrial network.
[src:powerlink/industrial-ethernet] Programmable logic controllers (PLCs) communicate using one of several possible open or proprietary protocols, such as EtherNet/IP, EtherCAT, Modbus, Sinec H1, Profibus, CANopen, DeviceNet or FOUNDATION Fieldbus.
[src:powerlink/industrial-ethernet] The idea to use standard Ethernet makes these systems more interoperable.
[src:powerlink/motion-control] Typically the position or velocity of machines are controlled using some type of device such as a hydraulic pump, linear actuator, or electric motor, generally a servo.
[src:powerlink/motion-control] Motion control is an important part of robotics and CNC machine tools, however in these instances it is more complex than when used with specialized machines, where the kinematics are usually simpler.
[src:powerlink/motion-control] The latter is often called General Motion Control (GMC).
[src:powerlink/motion-control] Motion control is widely used in the packaging, printing, textile, semiconductor production, and assembly industries.
[src:powerlink/motion-control] Motion Control encompasses every technology related to the movement of objects.
[src:powerlink/motion-control] It covers every motion system from micro-sized systems such as silicon-type micro induction actuators to micro-siml systems such as a space platform.
[src:powerlink/motion-control] But, these days, the focus of motion control is the special control technology of motion systems with electric actuators such as dc/ac servo motors.
[src:powerlink/motion-control] Control of robotic manipulators is also included in the field of motion control because most of robotic manipulators are driven by electrical servo motors and the key objective is the control of motion.
[src:powerlink/motion-control] The interface between the motion controller and drives it control is very critical when coordinated motion is required, as it must provide tight synchronization.
[src:powerlink/motion-control] Historically the only open interface was an analog signal, until open interfaces were developed that satisfied the requirements of coordinated motion control, the first being SERCOS in 1991 which is now enhanced to SERCOS III.
[src:powerlink/motion-control] Later interfaces capable of motion control include Ethernet/IP, Profinet IRT, Ethernet Powerlink, and EtherCAT.
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] The term "real-time" is also used in simulation to mean that the simulation's clock runs at the same speed as a real clock.
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] Real-time responses are often understood to be in the order of milliseconds, and sometimes microseconds.
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] A system not specified as operating in real time cannot usually *guarantee* a response within any timeframe, although *typical* or *expected* response times may be given.
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] Real-time processing *fails* if not completed within a specified deadline relative to an event; deadlines must always be met, regardless of system load.
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] A real-time system has been described as one which "controls an environment by receiving data, processing them, and returning the results sufficiently quickly to affect the environment at that time".
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] The term "real-time" is used in process control and enterprise systems to mean "without significant delay".
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] Real-time software may use one or more of the following: synchronous programming languages, real-time operating systems (RTOSes), and real-time networks.
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] Each of these provides essential frameworks on which to build a real-time software application.
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] Systems used for many safety-critical applications must be real-time, such as for control of fly-by-wire aircraft, or anti-lock brakes, both of which demand immediate and accurate mechanical response.
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] The term *real-time* derives from its use in early simulation, where a real-world process is simulated at a rate which matched that of the real process (now called real-time simulation to avoid ambiguity).
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] Analog computers, most often, were capable of simulating at a much faster pace than real-time, a situation that could be just as dangerous as a slow simulation if it were not also recognized and accounted for.
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] Minicomputers, particularly from the 1970s onwards, when built into dedicated embedded systems such as DOG (digital on-screen graphic) scanners, increased the need for low-latency priority-driven responses to important interactions with incoming data.
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] Operating systems such as Data General's RDOS (Real-Time Disk Operating System) and RTOS with background and foreground scheduling as well as Digital Equipment Corporation's RT-11 date from this era.
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] Background-foreground scheduling allowed low-priority tasks CPU time when no foreground task needed to execute, and gave absolute priority within the foreground to threads/tasks with the highest priority.
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] Real-time operating systems would also be used for time-sharing multiuser duties.
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] For example, Data General Business Basic could run in the foreground or background of RDOS and would introduce additional elements to the scheduling algorithm to make it more appropriate for people interacting via dumb terminals.
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] Early personal computers were sometimes used for real-time computing.
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] The possibility of deactivating other interrupts allowed for hard-coded loops with defined timing, and the low interrupt latency allowed the implementation of a real-time operating system, giving the user interface and the disk drives lower priority than the real-time thread.
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] However, several coding libraries exist that offer real-time capabilities in a high-level language on a variety of operating systems, for example, Real-time Java.
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] Later microprocessors such as the Motorola 68000 and subsequent family members (68010, 68020, ColdFire, etc.) also became popular with manufacturers of industrial control systems.
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] This application area is one where real-time control offers genuine advantages in terms of process performance and safety.
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] A system is said to be *real-time* if the total correctness of an operation depends not only upon its logical correctness, but also upon the time in which it is performed.
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] Thus, the goal of a *hard real-time system* is to ensure that all deadlines are met, but for *soft real-time systems* the goal becomes meeting a certain subset of deadlines in order to optimize some application-specific criteria.
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] The particular criteria optimized depend on the application, but some typical examples include maximizing the number of deadlines met, minimizing the lateness of tasks and maximizing the number of high-priority tasks meeting their deadlines.
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] In the context of multitasking systems the scheduling policy is normally priority driven (pre-emptive schedulers).
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] In some situations, these can guarantee hard real-time performance (for instance, if the set of tasks and their priorities is known in advance).
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] There are other hard real-time schedulers such as rate-monotonic, which is not common in general-purpose systems, as it requires additional information in order to schedule a task: namely, a bound or worst-case estimate for how long the task must execute.
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] Specific algorithms for scheduling such hard real-time tasks exist, like earliest deadline first, which, ignoring the overhead of context switching, is sufficient for system loads of less than 100%.
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] New overlay scheduling systems, such as an adaptive partition scheduler assist in managing large systems with a mixture of hard real-time and non real-time applications.
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] In a real-time digital signal processing (DSP) process, the analyzed (input) and generated (output) samples can be processed (or generated) continuously in the time it takes to input and output the same set of samples *independent* of the processing delay.
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] It means that the processing delay must be bounded even if the processing continues for an unlimited time.
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] The mean processing time per sample, including overhead, is no greater than the sampling period, which is the reciprocal of the sampling rate.
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] This is the criterion whether the samples are grouped together in large segments and processed as blocks or are processed individually and whether there are long, short, or non-existent input and output buffers.
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] Consider an audio DSP example; if a process requires 2.01 seconds to analyze, synthesize, or process 2.00 seconds of sound, it is not real-time.
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] However, if it takes 1.99 seconds, it is or can be made into a real-time DSP process.
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] A common life analogy is standing in a line or queue waiting for the checkout in a grocery store.
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] If the line asymptotically grows longer and longer without bound, the checkout process is not real-time.
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] If the length of the line is bounded, customers are being "processed" and output as rapidly, on average, as they are being inputted, then that process *is* real-time.
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] The grocer might go out of business or must at least lose business if they cannot make their checkout process real-time; thus, it is fundamentally important that this process is real-time.
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] A signal processing algorithm that cannot keep up with the flow of input data, with output falling further and further behind the input, is not real-time.
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] If the delay of the output (relative to the input) is bounded regarding a process that operates over an unlimited time, then that signal processing algorithm is real-time, even if the throughput delay may be very long.
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] Real-time signal processing is necessary, but not sufficient in and of itself, for live signal processing such as what is required in live event support.
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] Live audio digital signal processing requires both real-time operation and a sufficient limit to throughput delay so as to be tolerable to performers using stage monitors or in-ear monitors and not noticeable as lip sync error by the audience also directly watching the performers.
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] Tolerable limits to latency for live, real-time processing is a subject of investigation and debate, but is estimated to be between 6 and 20 milliseconds.
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] Real-time bidirectional telecommunications delays of less than 300 ms ("round trip" or twice the unidirectional delay) are considered "acceptable" to avoid undesired "talk-over" in conversation.
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] Real-time computing is sometimes misunderstood to be high-performance computing, but this is not an accurate classification.
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] For example, a massive supercomputer executing a scientific simulation may offer impressive performance, yet it is not executing a real-time computation.
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] Conversely, once the hardware and software for an anti-lock braking system have been designed to meet its required deadlines, no further performance gains are obligatory or even useful.
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] Furthermore, if a network server is highly loaded with network traffic, its response time may be slower, but will (in most cases) still succeed before it times out (hits its deadline).
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] Hence, such a network server would not be considered a real-time system: temporal failures (delays, time-outs, etc.) are typically small and compartmentalized (limited in effect), but are not catastrophic failures.
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] In a real-time system, such as the FTSE 100 Index, a slowdown beyond limits would often be considered catastrophic in its application context.
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] The most important requirement of a real-time system is consistent output, not high throughput.
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] Some kinds of software, such as many chess-playing programs, can fall into either category.
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] For instance, a chess program designed to play in a tournament with a clock will need to decide on a move before a certain deadline or lose the game, and is therefore a real-time computation, but a chess program that is allowed to run indefinitely before moving is not.
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] In both of these cases, however, high performance is desirable: the more work a tournament chess program can do in the allotted time, the better its moves will be, and the faster an unconstrained chess program runs, the sooner it will be able to move.
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] High performance is indicative of the amount of processing that is performed in a given amount of time, whereas real-time is the ability to get done with the processing to yield a useful output in the available time.
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] For example, a near-real-time display depicts an event or situation as it existed at the current time minus the processing time, as nearly the time of the live event.
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] The distinction between the terms "near real time" and "real time" is somewhat nebulous and must be defined for the situation at hand.
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] The term implies that there are no significant delays.
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] In many cases, processing described as "real-time" would be more accurately described as "near real-time".
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] Near real-time also refers to delayed real-time transmission of voice and video.
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] It allows playing video images, in approximately real-time, without having to wait for an entire large video file to download.
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] Incompatible databases can export/import to common flat files that the other database can import/export on a scheduled basis so they can sync/share common data in "near real-time" with each other.
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] Several methods exist to aid the design of real-time systems, an example of which is MASCOT, an old but very successful method that represents the concurrent structure of the system.
[src:powerlink/real-time-computing] Other examples are HOOD, Real-Time UML, AADL, the Ravenscar profile, and Real-time Java.
[src:powerlink/time-division-multiple-access] TDMA is a type of time-division multiplexing (TDM), with the special point that instead of having one transmitter connected to one receiver, there are multiple transmitters.
[src:powerlink/time-division-multiple-access] TDMA is used in digital 2G cellular systems such as Global System for Mobile Communications (GSM), IS-136, Personal Digital Cellular (PDC) and iDEN, in the Maritime Automatic Identification System, and in the Digital Enhanced Cordless Telecommunications (DECT) standard for portable phones.
[src:powerlink/time-division-multiple-access] TDMA was first used in satellite communication systems by Western Union in its Westar 3 communications satellite in 1979.
[src:powerlink/time-division-multiple-access] It is now used extensively in satellite communications, combat-net radio systems, and passive optical network (PON) networks for upstream traffic from premises to the operator.
[src:powerlink/time-division-multiple-access] Most 2G cellular systems, with the notable exception of IS-95, are based on TDMA.
[src:powerlink/time-division-multiple-access] GSM, D-AMPS, PDC, iDEN, and PHS are all examples of TDMA cellular systems.
[src:powerlink/time-division-multiple-access] In the GSM system, the synchronization of the mobile phones is achieved by sending timing advance commands from the base station, which instruct the mobile phone to transmit earlier and by how much.
[src:powerlink/time-division-multiple-access] This compensates for the speed-of-light propagation delay between phone and base station.
[src:powerlink/time-division-multiple-access] The mobile phone is not allowed to transmit for its entire time slot; there is a guard interval at the end of each time slot.
[src:powerlink/time-division-multiple-access] As the transmission moves into the guard period, the mobile network updates the timing advance to synchronize the transmission.
[src:powerlink/time-division-multiple-access] Initial synchronization of a phone requires a special procedure.
[src:powerlink/time-division-multiple-access] Before a mobile transmits, there is no way to know the timing advance required.
[src:powerlink/time-division-multiple-access] For this reason, an entire time slot is dedicated to mobiles attempting to contact the network; this is known as the random-access channel (RACH) in GSM.
[src:powerlink/time-division-multiple-access] The mobile transmits at the beginning of the time slot as received from the network.
[src:powerlink/time-division-multiple-access] If the mobile is near the base station, the propagation delay is short and the initiation can succeed.
[src:powerlink/time-division-multiple-access] If, however, the mobile phone is farther than 35 km from the base station, the delay will mean the mobile's transmission arrives at the end of the time slot.
[src:powerlink/time-division-multiple-access] In this case, the mobile will be instructed to transmit its messages starting nearly a whole time slot earlier so that it can be received at the proper time.
[src:powerlink/time-division-multiple-access] Finally, if the mobile is beyond the 35 km cell range of GSM, the transmission will arrive in a neighbouring time slot and be ignored.
[src:powerlink/time-division-multiple-access] It is this feature, rather than limitations of power, that limits the range of a GSM cell to 35 km when no special extension techniques are used.
[src:powerlink/time-division-multiple-access] By changing the synchronization between the uplink and downlink at the base station, however, this limitation can be overcome.
[src:powerlink/time-division-multiple-access] UTRA-FDD (frequency division duplex) employs CDMA and FDD, where separate frequency bands are allocated for uplink and downlink transmissions.
[src:powerlink/time-division-multiple-access] This separation minimizes interference and allows for continuous data transmission in both directions, making it suitable for environments with balanced traffic loads.
[src:powerlink/time-division-multiple-access] UTRA-TDD (time division duplex), on the other hand, combines CDMA with TDMA and TDD.
[src:powerlink/time-division-multiple-access] In this scheme, the same frequency band is used for both uplink and downlink, but at different times.
[src:powerlink/time-division-multiple-access] This time-based separation is particularly advantageous in scenarios with asymmetric traffic loads, where the data rates for uplink and downlink differ significantly.
[src:powerlink/time-division-multiple-access] By dynamically allocating time slots based on demand, UTRA-TDD can efficiently manage varying traffic patterns and enhance overall network capacity.
[src:powerlink/time-division-multiple-access] The combination of these technologies in UMTS allows for more flexible and efficient use of the available spectrum, catering to diverse user demands and improving the adaptability of 3G networks to different operational environments.
[src:powerlink/time-division-multiple-access] The ITU-T G.hn standard, which provides high-speed local area networking over existing home wiring (power lines, phone lines and coaxial cables) is based on a TDMA scheme.
[src:powerlink/time-division-multiple-access] In G.hn, a *master* device allocates *contention-free transmission opportunities* (CFTXOP) to other *slave* devices in the network.
[src:powerlink/time-division-multiple-access] Only one device can use a CFTXOP at a time, thus avoiding collisions.
[src:powerlink/time-division-multiple-access] FlexRay protocol, which is also a wired network used for safety-critical communication in modern cars, uses the TDMA method for data transmission control.
[src:powerlink/time-division-multiple-access] In radio systems, TDMA is usually used alongside frequency-division multiple access (FDMA) and frequency-division duplex (FDD); the combination is referred to as FDMA/TDMA/FDD.
[src:powerlink/time-division-multiple-access] This is the case in both GSM and IS-136, for example.
[src:powerlink/time-division-multiple-access] Exceptions to this include the DECT and Personal Handy-phone System (PHS) micro-cellular systems, UMTS-TDD UMTS variant, and China's TD-SCDMA, which use time-division duplexing, where different time slots are allocated for the base station and handsets on the same frequency.
[src:powerlink/time-division-multiple-access] A major advantage of TDMA is that the radio part of the mobile phone only needs to listen and broadcast for its own time slot.
[src:powerlink/time-division-multiple-access] For the rest of the time, the mobile can carry out measurements on the network, detecting surrounding transmitters on different frequencies.
[src:powerlink/time-division-multiple-access] This allows safe inter-frequency handovers, something which is difficult in CDMA systems, not supported at all in IS-95 and supported through complex system additions in Universal Mobile Telecommunications System (UMTS).
[src:powerlink/time-division-multiple-access] This, in turn, allows for co-existence of microcell layers with macrocell layers.
[src:powerlink/time-division-multiple-access] CDMA, by comparison, supports *soft hand-off*, which allows a mobile phone to be in communication with up to 6 base stations simultaneously, a type of *same-frequency handover*.
[src:powerlink/time-division-multiple-access] The incoming packets are compared for quality, and the best one is selected.
[src:powerlink/time-division-multiple-access] CDMA's *cell breathing* characteristic, where a terminal on the boundary of two congested cells will be unable to receive a clear signal, can often negate this advantage during peak periods.
[src:powerlink/time-division-multiple-access] A disadvantage of TDMA systems is that they create interference at a frequency that is directly connected to the time slot length.
[src:powerlink/time-division-multiple-access] This is the buzz that can sometimes be heard if a TDMA phone is left next to a radio or speakers.
[src:powerlink/time-division-multiple-access] Another disadvantage is that the *dead time* between time slots limits the potential bandwidth of a TDMA channel.
[src:powerlink/time-division-multiple-access] These are implemented in part because of the difficulty in ensuring that different terminals transmit at exactly the times required.
[src:powerlink/time-division-multiple-access] Handsets that are moving will need to constantly adjust their timings to ensure their transmission is received at precisely the right time, because as they move further from the base station, their signal will take longer to arrive.
[src:powerlink/time-division-multiple-access] This also means that the major TDMA systems have hard limits on cell sizes in terms of range, though in practice, the power levels required to receive and transmit over distances greater than the supported range would be mostly impractical anyway.
[src:powerlink/time-division-multiple-access] In **dynamic time-division multiple access** (**dynamic TDMA**), a scheduling algorithm dynamically reserves a variable number of time slots in each frame to variable bit-rate data streams, based on the traffic demand of each data stream.
